thor</font></td><td valign=top bgcolor=d1c3b5 class=headings><font color=#000000>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/uchasefv.showPublicProfile?language=EN>ChaseFV</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 29<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(8/13/02 8:56:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1174.topic&index=19>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_tongue.gif" align=absmiddle>  Ah, competition. Oh, joy.</span><hr size=1> You set your prices at what's good for you, I'll set my prices at what's good for me, and I'll piss and moan about how you're starving my children. <br>
<br>
I typically set my prices at a level I think is fair (covers costs, provides a little profit for me), but I do compare it to the price others are charging. I will typically match the lowest price being charged by someone who has at least a stack in inventory, unless I think that price is just silly. As you mentioned, the bottom has completely fallen out of the Ohabah Truffle market, due in large part to people's ability to produce them in bulk (once saw 3 vendors on with over 100 each), and their willingness to sell them dirt cheap (5gp each was the lowest price I saw, and I still refuse to match that).<br>
<br>
Now, as to the under-cutting: if, as you claim, you set your price at what you feel is fair, you still clear a profit on those items, and you don't change your prices based on the presence of competition in the Bazaar, then I have no grounds for complaint. I guess I just feel that my time spent farming/foraging/gathering is worth more PP/hour than you do.<br>
<br>
I concur that price fixing is unfair to the consumer, but there is an organization being proposed down in the Tradeskills shop that proposes that very thing. It works out to the best interest of the seller (and let's face it, when it comes down to it, we all look out for number one first), and it provides the consumer with a fair price, and a reasonable expectation of being able to obtain the same item at the same (or at least a similar) price in the future. As we've discussed, these are consumables, and our most ideal market would be repeat business. Someone coming in and finding QAT for 10pp/each is going to be much less eager to buy from someone charging 30/pp each after they run out. However if there is less variation in the price (noticed you were up to 20pp/each last night), then the expectation is set that this item will fall within a specific range, and the consumer will not be dissatisfied if the merchant selling at 20pp/each is out, and they have to hit the merchant charging 30pp/each to refill their stock.<br>
<br>
Let's break down the cost of actually making, say, 24 attempts at QAT:<br>
<br>
24 Tea Leaves (foraged - let's call it 4 hours spent in EK or 5PP/each -- what I've seen them for at the Bazaar). Total - 120PP<br>
<br>
24 Cream (4 successful combines of 2 milk, 1 benzoin (2PP), and 1 dairy spoon, in a mixing bowl (2PP)) - 10PP<br>
<br>
24 celestial essence (1 celestial solvent (1pp?) 1 research item (2.5PP)) 84PP<br>
<br>
24 Bayle's Delight (2 successful combines of 1 griffon feather (10PP), 1 water, and 1 King's Thorn (5PP?)) 30PP<br>
<br>
24 water flasks<br>
<br>
24 Eucalyptus (5PP) 120PP<br>
<br>
So the ball park total for this many attempts is 364PP. Assuming a 50% success rate (as we have no one who has come forth as a GM brewer yet to my knowledge) that yields 72 teas (prolly more like 80-90), which could be sold at about 5PP each to cover costs. 10PP is apparently a fair price based on this math. But it doesn't take into account the time, money and effort spent pushing your brewing up to the point where you have a reasonable chance of success making this item. So given my desire to be compensated for the effort I've put in to skilling up, and my desire to earn some additional cash to skill up further, I'm charging 30PP until someone out-produces me and undercharges, flooding the market.<br>
<br>
At any rate, as I mentioned way back up at the top of this response, I mostly just wanted to bitch, and poke a little fun at you for complaining that no one was buying, then selling at less than the competition (as I mentioned - a perfectly fair marketing ploy, but I don't have to like it) (and didn't I see you on the thread complaining about undercutters?). As tradeskillers, we should charge what we feel is fair; you and I simply have differing concepts of what that is, and that is ok. <br>
<br>
Hope I didn't lower your gruntle meter too much,<br>
Chase<br>
<br>
